17.  Conclusion
The MTS framework yields a transport-response law for disk galaxies with cosmological normalisation, photometric scale closure, zero-parameter memory correction, and emergent response branching. LTGs follow a closed first-order law. ETGs form a multi-family, multi-sign response sector with a layered structure: an inner baryonic overshoot gate (Ω_in > 1), a positive backbone whose inner scale and outer channel count are set by galaxy structure, and a suppression channel whose amplitude decomposes into a hard observable lower bound plus a residual excess term.

The sign-changing behaviour of H+ ETGs is a structural consequence of the outer-dominated backbone geometry combined with a transport-derived suppression operator — not a sign change in any coupling constant. The corrected-sign inner balance reveals a clean decomposition λ_B = λ_min + λ_exc where λ_min = |ΔV²_in|/G_supp is fixed by observables alone. The suppression integral G_supp must be computed via the IBP form using the normalised inner profile B(y), not a derivative-based approximation; the IBP form reveals the exact decomposition κ* = exp(−1/x_B) + U, where U is the kernel-weighted unfinished baryonic rise.  The single-channel H+ branch is governed by a near-invariant branch constant U_* ≈ 0.202 (CV = 2.04%), which is the image of the empirical law x_B ≈ 3.34(1 − Q₁₂) under the full-profile kernel map. This scaling is structurally derived: choosing x_B ∝ Δ = 1 − Q₁₂ is the unique substitution that removes the explicit deficit amplitude from the U prefactor, leaving a kernel-weighted integral J of the normalised profile shape H(y) = (1 − B(y))/Δ. The branch condition J(A) = A · U_* determines the coefficient A ≈ 3.34 empirically from 3 calibrators; the coefficient reflects the near-coincidence of the three J_i(A) curves at a common target level.  The viable single-channel branch requires two simultaneous feasibility conditions: outer capacity (u ≤ 1) and inner kernel capacity (U_* ≤ U_max(B)). NGC4203 violates both independently. The global disk scale length h is not fundamental to the branch; the canonical suppression scale is L_B = x_loc · r_in, where x_loc is the profile-defined high-root of U(x_B; B) = U_*. This eliminates dependence on unstable disk decompositions for polar-ring and counter-rotating systems. The strongest H+ case (NGC4203) requires a second outer backbone channel and is best understood as an outer-capacity failure, not an extreme inner-memory object.



18.  Methods and Data
Data: SPARC ROTMOD files (Lelli et al. 2016, 175 galaxies). ETG rotation curves from ATLAS³D (16 galaxies, 2 observed points each). ETG photometric decompositions: Laurikainen et al. 2011 (MNRAS 418:1452; NIRS0S atlas). Note: external h values from Laurikainen et al. 2011 are not used in the canonical pipeline (§12.4); internal profile-defined x_loc is the correct branch variable.

Baryonic convention: V_bar² = V_gas² + 0.5 V_disk² + 0.7 V_bulge²

Cleaning: finite values, r > 0, V_obs > 0, sorted, duplicates removed.

Scale lengths: h from SBdisk exponential fits (LTGs); disk-density exponential fits from component profiles (ETGs, used as approximate proxy only). For H+ single-channel ETGs, the canonical suppression scale is L_B = x_loc · r_in where x_loc is the profile-defined high-root of U(x_B; B) = U_* (§12.4), replacing the old L_B = 0.2h proxy.

Derived quantities: V_bar,char = max(V_bar); j_bar = ∫ r V_bar² dr / ∫ V_bar dr; R_outer = max(r); f_gas = V_gas²(R_outer) / V_bar²(R_outer).

Evaluation: RMSE = sqrt(mean[(V_model − V_obs)²]).

ETG H+ gate: Ω_in = V_bar²(r_inner)/V_obs²(r_inner) > 1, verified from raw files with zero false positives and zero misses across all 16 ETGs.
